{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"alias":"giddying-teenytiny-mare","description":"## Why\nThe rising floor's remediation-mode eligibility (src/rebar/llm/plan_review/attest.py::remediation_mode_candidate) requires a prior CERTIFIED plan-review signature (\"signed\"). A BLOCK never signs, so the floor is structurally inert in BLOCK loops - the regime driving 76% of extra review rounds. Post-flip field data: 287/382 plan reviews ineligible (240 with signed=False as the first failing precondition), 33 eligible, 0 novelty drops ever. The floor only drops advisories, but BLOCK-loop advisory walls balloon (ticket 36c7: 21 -> 36 advisories over 10 rounds), so engaging it there is real relief.\n\n## What\n- Rekey eligibility off the prior REVIEW_RESULT sidecar instead of the certified signature: baseline material fingerprint and reviewed-code SHA come from the most recent sidecar (material_fingerprint is already persisted; persist the review-time code SHA alongside it if not already present), preserving the same precondition semantics: plan CHANGED since last review, code UNCHANGED, registry version unchanged, within the freshness window.\n- The signature-based path remains valid when present (a signed baseline is still the strongest reference); the sidecar path is the fallback that makes BLOCK loops eligible.\n- SEQUENCING: epic/audit-enrichment (ba33 / courtly-linear-iguana) rewrites attest.py (extracts manifest.py) and enriches the plan sidecar (lossless v2). This story MUST NOT start until that epic's plan-review commits are on main; it builds on the post-rewrite attest/manifest/sidecar shape. relates_to link records the dependency without promoting a blocking link.\n\n## Scope\nIN: eligibility rekey, sidecar field addition if needed, docs update in docs/plan-review-gate.md (replacing the honest-limitation paragraph added by the docs child of this epic), unit tests over the eligibility decision matrix. OUT: the drop math (novelty threshold/priority floor unchanged), the novelty scorer itself (see the eval task in this epic), drop permanence semantics.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] With no certified signature but a prior sidecar (plan changed, code + registry unchanged, within window), remediation eligibility is TRUE. Oracle: unit test over remediation_mode_candidate (or its post-refactor successor) with a fixture sidecar; `python -m pytest tests/unit -k \"remediation\" -x` green.\n- [ ] With code drifted since the prior sidecar, eligibility is FALSE (unchanged fail-safe). Oracle: negative-case unit test in the same module.\n- [ ] A BLOCK-loop integration test (review -> BLOCK -> plan edit -> re-review) reaches the floor path (eligibility TRUE on round 2) without any signature present. Oracle: integration test asserting coverage.remediation.eligible is true in the round-2 sidecar.\n- [ ] docs/plan-review-gate.md's eligibility description matches the new behavior. Oracle: `grep -n \"certified\" docs/plan-review-gate.md` shows no claim that eligibility requires a certified signature.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` all pass.","id":"a850-1392-55b0-4514","parent_id":"d195-aeb8-2400-484b","priority":2,"tags":[],"ticket_type":"story","title":"Rekey rising-floor eligibility off prior sidecar so BLOCK loops qualify"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1784085097670668001,"uuid":"8808762e-a9a9-46e3-ae38-b446826d28e9"}